40|$|The Leak in of <b>glass</b> <b>melt</b> {{into the}} <b>glass</b> moulds yet not been {{determined}} in "the real conditions of mass production". The mold filling was evaluated through <b>glass</b> <b>melt</b> viscosity measurements. Viscosity is physical quantity, but it does't include additional significant effects, like surface roughness, lubrication, tension inside the mould a. o. On {{the ground of}} this we decided to propose methodology of leak in measurement test not only in term of physical, but also of real condition in general practice, i. e. technological test. In the glass production is generated ineligible descreasing of quality of glass products because of interaction metal versus <b>glass</b> <b>melt.</b> The quality of glass equipment surface has a substantial effect on surface quality of glass product. The metal surface degrades because of a long-term cyclic contact with a hot <b>glass</b> <b>melt.</b> The character of degrading process affects the lifetime of materials applied in glass production. Because of these factors, we realized proposed technological test on presented glass equipment with various surface qualities and for different temperatures...|$|R
40|$|In {{the present}} research, surface tension and density of {{borosilicate}} melts were measured and {{compared to that}} of Na-Ca containing <b>glass</b> <b>melt</b> using sessile drop method. The results show that the density of borosilicate melt, always lower than that of Na-Ca containing <b>glass</b> <b>melt,</b> decreases linearly with temperature rising. The temperature dependence of density indicates a lower thermal expansion coefficient of borosilicate melt. The surface tension of both borosilicate and Na-Ca containing <b>glass</b> <b>melts</b> increases linearly with temperature within 1000 degrees C similar to 1200 degrees C and temperature coefficients are 0. 27867 and 0. 11867, respectively. It is reasonable to deduce that higher surface tension and temperature coefficient of borosilicate melt are attributed to the effect of boron oxide...|$|R
